#) What is JavaScript Temporal?
    - Temporal is the new standard for date and time in JavaScript.
    - Temporal is a built-in JavaScript API that provides date and time objects that are easier and
        safer to use than Date.
    - New Temporal objects was designed to replace the old Date object.
    - Unlike legacy Date, Temporal objects are immutable(meaning they cannot be changed after they
        are created) and provide first-class support for time
        zones, daylight saving time (DST), date math and non-Gregorian calendars.
    - Temporal separates date and time into distinct classes to prevent "wall-clock" errors.

        Feature	                    Date	        Temporal
    -------------------------------------------------------------------
        Mutable (can change)	    Yes	            No
        Time zone handling	        Limited	        Built-in
        DST safe math	            No	            Yes
        Modern API design	        No	            Yes


#) Why Was Temporal Created?
    - The Date object was created in 1995 and has some design issues that still cause bugs today.
    - For example, âš ï¸ months in Date are zero-based, which is confusing.
            let d = new Date(2026, 0, 17); // Month 0 = January
    
    - âš ï¸Another problem is that many Date methods change the same object (mutation), which can create
        unexpected results.
            let d = new Date(); // current date: Tue Feb 24 2026 20:10:55 GMT+0545 (Nepal Time)
            d.setDate(d.getDate() + 7); // getDate returns the day of a date as a number (1-31) i.e, 24
                                            setDate sets the day of the date object so new day will be
                                            24+7 = 31
    
    - ğŸ’¡Temporal was created to solve these issues with clearer object types and predictable behavior.


#) A Simple Temporal Example:
    - With Temporal, you can get today's date and add days in a clear and safe way.
            let today = Temporal.Now.plainDateISO();
            let nextWeek = today.add({ days: 7 });


#) DST-Safe Arithmetic:
    - DST-safe arithmetic ensures time calculations (addition and subtraction) remain accurate across
        Daylight Saving Time (DST) transitions, preventing 1-hour errors.
    - It involves using timezone and calendar-aware objects (ZonedDateTime) that understand local
        clock shifts.


#) RFC 5545 iCalendar:
    - RFC 5545, titled iCalendar (Internet Calendaring and Scheduling Core Object Specification), is
        the industry standard for exchanging calendar and scheduling information.
    - It allows different systems (like Google Calendar, Apple Calendar, and Microsoft Outlook) to
        communicate seamlessly.


#) When Should You Use Temporal?
    - Use Temporal when you need reliable date and time handling.
        ğŸ‘‰ You need correct time zone support.
        ğŸ‘‰ You want safe date arithmetic (add or subtract days, months, years).
        ğŸ‘‰ You want to avoid DST bugs.
        ğŸ‘‰ You want predictable and readable code.

    - You may still use Date for very simple tasks, or when you must support environments where Temporal is
        not available.


#) Temporal Object Types
    - Temporal includes several object types for different kinds of date and time values:
        ğŸ’¡ Temporal.Instant - An exact moment in time (UTC timestamp).
        ğŸ’¡ Temporal.PlainDate - A date only (year, month, day).
        ğŸ’¡ Temporal.PlainDateTime - Date and time without a time zone.
        ğŸ’¡Temporal.ZonedDateTime - Date and time with a time zone.
        ğŸ’¡ Temporal.Duration - A length of time (days, hours, minutes).

    - Later, you will learn how each type works and when to use it.